1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,610
In this short demo, let's go over a couple of

2
00:00:02,610 --> 00:00:05,685
Pandas' methods for programmatically accessing data structure,

3
00:00:05,685 --> 00:00:09,765
which often involves a combination of visual and programmatic assessment.

4
00:00:09,765 --> 00:00:12,825
Again, we're picking on our synthetic clinical trial data,

5
00:00:12,825 --> 00:00:15,015
this time looking at a couple of tables.

6
00:00:15,015 --> 00:00:19,500
Here, the new table that we're adding in is our adverse reactions table that's centered

7
00:00:19,500 --> 00:00:24,295
around telling us the adverse reactions that patients had as a result of the treatment.

8
00:00:24,295 --> 00:00:28,700
In this demo, focusing on the patient's treatments and adverse reactions tables,

9
00:00:28,700 --> 00:00:30,140
let's go ahead and take a look at

10
00:00:30,140 --> 00:00:33,925
the first few rows of the tables using the dot head function.

11
00:00:33,925 --> 00:00:36,680
Note how the adverse reactions tables,

12
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:38,195
including the name of patients,

13
00:00:38,195 --> 00:00:40,250
their first name and their last name essentially,

14
00:00:40,250 --> 00:00:43,300
as two individual columns and the adverse reaction.

15
00:00:43,300 --> 00:00:47,675
We also have the visual inspection for the treatments DataFrame here as well.

16
00:00:47,675 --> 00:00:50,995
Let's use one of the functions we're familiar with,.info.

17
00:00:50,995 --> 00:00:54,945
We're going to start using.info to inspect our two tables.

18
00:00:54,945 --> 00:00:58,790
Let's go ahead and skip over to the adverse reactions inspection.

19
00:00:58,790 --> 00:01:03,745
Notice how there are only 34 entries in the adverse reactions DataFrame.

20
00:01:03,745 --> 00:01:06,010
We can use a few other methods to closely

21
00:01:06,010 --> 00:01:08,410
inspect some of the columns and shape information.

22
00:01:08,410 --> 00:01:11,200
For example, let's get the.shape using

23
00:01:11,200 --> 00:01:15,185
the.shape method on the adverse reactions DataFrame.

24
00:01:15,185 --> 00:01:18,310
Here we're getting the dimensionality of the DataFrame showing us

25
00:01:18,310 --> 00:01:21,445
that the table has 34 rows and three columns.

26
00:01:21,445 --> 00:01:24,160
We can also use the columns method to get

27
00:01:24,160 --> 00:01:27,050
all of the column labels in our dataset programmatically.

28
00:01:27,050 --> 00:01:29,860
Finally, we can also use the.index method to

29
00:01:29,860 --> 00:01:32,515
understand the index of the adverse reactions table,

30
00:01:32,515 --> 00:01:35,005
in this case ranging from 0-34.

31
00:01:35,005 --> 00:01:39,220
While this doesn't seem particularly useful for this dataset right now,

32
00:01:39,220 --> 00:01:44,185
for datasets with more complex indexes and for operations like dropping duplicate rows,

33
00:01:44,185 --> 00:01:47,630
it can be helpful to quickly access the index.

34
00:01:47,810 --> 00:01:51,020
Now with all of this information that we've gathered,

35
00:01:51,020 --> 00:01:54,155
we can start to make some assessments around the data structure.

36
00:01:54,155 --> 00:01:58,100
We can start to determine that the adverse reaction column of

37
00:01:58,100 --> 00:02:00,200
the adverse reactions table should actually be

38
00:02:00,200 --> 00:02:03,275
included in the treatments table through visual assessment.

39
00:02:03,275 --> 00:02:06,770
Why? Well, when looking at the treatments table here below,

40
00:02:06,770 --> 00:02:10,040
we can see that the adverse reaction for that treatment

41
00:02:10,040 --> 00:02:13,490
has same observational unit as the treatments table,

42
00:02:13,490 --> 00:02:16,655
which is the treatment data for an individual patient.

43
00:02:16,655 --> 00:02:19,280
Since the given name and surname columns are

44
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:22,430
present in both the adverse reactions and treatments tables,

45
00:02:22,430 --> 00:02:23,645
when cleaning the dataset,

46
00:02:23,645 --> 00:02:28,565
we can use these two variables to combine the two tables into a single table.

47
00:02:28,565 --> 00:02:30,615
This is a case of an issue,

48
00:02:30,615 --> 00:02:34,210
a single observational unit is being stored in multiple tables.

49
00:02:34,210 --> 00:02:36,405
Here are a few additional issues.

50
00:02:36,405 --> 00:02:41,165
We can visually see a case where variables are stored in both rows and columns.

51
00:02:41,165 --> 00:02:45,020
In the treatment table, the Auralin and Novodra columns contain three variables.

52
00:02:45,020 --> 00:02:47,000
Which treatment the patient is using,

53
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:48,605
Auralin or Novodra,

54
00:02:48,605 --> 00:02:50,360
which is stored in the header row,

55
00:02:50,360 --> 00:02:54,530
and the start dose and the end dose separated by the dash.

56
00:02:54,530 --> 00:02:58,430
Let's use programmatic assessment to supplement our visual assessment.

57
00:02:58,430 --> 00:03:02,480
We can programmatically verify that an individual patient is recorded as

58
00:03:02,480 --> 00:03:04,760
taking only one drug by

59
00:03:04,760 --> 00:03:07,520
checking that the corresponding column for the other drug is empty.

60
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:10,135
For instance, if a patient is taking Novodra,

61
00:03:10,135 --> 00:03:14,660
their record should have values in the Novodra column and be empty in the Auralin column.

62
00:03:14,660 --> 00:03:18,230
In other words, no patients should be taking both drugs simultaneously.

63
00:03:18,230 --> 00:03:23,600
The Auralin and Novodra columns can both have values at the same time. Let's check this.

64
00:03:23,600 --> 00:03:25,460
We can do this by getting the rows where

65
00:03:25,460 --> 00:03:30,275
both the Auralin and Novodra columns are not empty in our treatments' DataFrame.

66
00:03:30,275 --> 00:03:35,880
We can see that there are no cases of rows that are applying to this case.

67
00:03:35,880 --> 00:03:37,190
In the cleaning stage,

68
00:03:37,190 --> 00:03:39,320
we can actually simplify our data structure and

69
00:03:39,320 --> 00:03:42,050
solve this issue by creating three new columns.

70
00:03:42,050 --> 00:03:44,780
One for the treatment specifying Auralin or Novodra,

71
00:03:44,780 --> 00:03:46,220
another for the starting dose,

72
00:03:46,220 --> 00:03:47,870
and a third for the ending dose.

73
00:03:47,870 --> 00:03:52,130
This updated structure will make it easier to analyze and work with the data while

74
00:03:52,130 --> 00:03:54,215
ensuring that there are no inconsistencies

75
00:03:54,215 --> 00:03:57,235
regarding patients taking both drugs simultaneously.

76
00:03:57,235 --> 00:04:01,640
Let's take a look at the patient's DataFrame and actually turn to another issue.

77
00:04:01,640 --> 00:04:04,220
We can visually see through the.head function and

78
00:04:04,220 --> 00:04:07,100
issue of multiple variables being stored in one column.

79
00:04:07,100 --> 00:04:10,775
The contact column in the patient's table contains two variables,

80
00:04:10,775 --> 00:04:13,995
phone number, and email.

81
00:04:13,995 --> 00:04:18,560
Let's investigate this further programmatically from a validity standpoint.

82
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:22,325
Are all the values in our data following the format of email,

83
00:04:22,325 --> 00:04:26,150
no space by immediately followed by a phone number?

84
00:04:26,150 --> 00:04:28,910
Using value counts, we can actually see

85
00:04:28,910 --> 00:04:31,315
that one of the values in our dataset for example,

86
00:04:31,315 --> 00:04:36,145
is actually violating this with the phone number first followed by the email.

87
00:04:36,145 --> 00:04:38,720
Because of this, it's going to be challenging to use

88
00:04:38,720 --> 00:04:40,950
string manipulation to parse and separate these.

89
00:04:40,950 --> 00:04:46,280
Because there isn't any standard format that these combined data points are following.

90
00:04:46,280 --> 00:04:48,410
We need to make sure that this issue is solved in

91
00:04:48,410 --> 00:04:50,630
the cleaning stage by creating two columns,

92
00:04:50,630 --> 00:04:54,420
one for the email address and the other for phone number.

